#: src/basics.md:1
msgid "Basic usage"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:3
msgid "Keeping Rust up to date"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust is distributed on three different [release channels](concepts/channels."
"md): stable, beta, and nightly. `rustup` uses the stable channel by default, "
"which represents the latest release of Rust. Stable publishes new releases "
"every six weeks."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:11
msgid ""
"When a new version of Rust is released, simply type `rustup update` to "
"update:"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:31
msgid "Keeping `rustup` up to date"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:33
msgid ""
"If your `rustup` was built with the [no-self-update feature](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rustup/blob/HEAD/Cargo.toml#L29), it can not update itself. "
"This is not the default, and only versions of `rustup` built with `--no-"
"default-features`, or obtained from a third-party distributor who has "
"disabled it (such as NixOS)."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:38
msgid ""
"Otherwise Rustup can update itself. It is possible to control Rustup's "
"automatic self update mechanism with the `auto-self-update` configuration "
"variable. This setting supports three values: `enable` and `disable` and "
"`check-only`."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:42
msgid ""
"`disable` will ensure that no automatic self updating actions are taken."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:43
msgid ""
"`enable` will mean that `rustup update` and similar commands will also check "
"for, and install, any update to Rustup."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:44
msgid ""
"`check-only` will cause any automatic self update to check and report on any "
"updates, but not to automatically install them."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:46
msgid ""
"Whether `auto-self-update` is `enable` or not, you can request that Rustup "
"update itself to the latest version of `rustup` by running `rustup self "
"update`. This will not download new toolchains:"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:56
msgid "Disabling self updates on a per-invocation basis"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:57
msgid ""
"Self updates can also be suppressed on individual invocations of `rustup` by "
"passing the argument `--no-self-update`  when running `rustup update` or "
"`rustup toolchain install`."
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:61
msgid "Help system"
msgstr ""

#: src/basics.md:63
msgid ""
"The `rustup` command-line has a built-in help system that provides more "
"information about each command. Run `rustup help` for an overview. Detailed "
"help for each subcommand is also available. For example, run `rustup "
"toolchain install --help` for specifics on installing [toolchains](concepts/"
"toolchains.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:1
msgid "Concepts"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:3
msgid "How rustup works"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:5
msgid ""
"`rustup` is a _toolchain multiplexer_. It installs and manages many Rust "
"toolchains and presents them all through a single set of tools installed to "
"`~/.cargo/bin`. The [`rustc`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/) and [`cargo`]"
"(https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/) executables installed in `~/.cargo/bin` "
"are _[proxies](proxies.md)_ that delegate to the real toolchain. `rustup` "
"then provides mechanisms to easily change the active toolchain by "
"reconfiguring the behavior of the proxies."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:12
msgid ""
"So when `rustup` is first installed, running `rustc` will run the proxy in "
"`$HOME/.cargo/bin/rustc`, which in turn will run the stable compiler. If you "
"later _change the default toolchain_ to nightly with `rustup default "
"nightly`, then that same proxy will run the `nightly` compiler instead."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:17
msgid ""
"This is similar to Ruby's [rbenv](https://github.com/rbenv/rbenv), Python's "
"[pyenv](https://github.com/yyuu/pyenv), or Node's [nvm](https://github.com/"
"creationix/nvm)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:26
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:28
msgid ""
"**channel** --- Rust is released to three different \"channels\": stable, "
"beta, and nightly. See the [Channels](channels.md) chapter for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:31
msgid ""
"**toolchain** --- A \"toolchain\" is a complete installation of the Rust "
"compiler (`rustc`) and related tools (like `cargo`). A [toolchain "
"specification](toolchains.md) includes the release channel or version, and "
"the host platform that the toolchain runs on."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:36
msgid ""
"**target** --- `rustc` is capable of generating code for many platforms. The "
"\"target\" specifies the platform that the code will be generated for. By "
"default, `cargo` and `rustc` use the host toolchain's platform as the "
"target. To build for a different target, usually the target's standard "
"library needs to be installed first via the `rustup target` command. See the "
"[Cross-compilation](../cross-compilation.md) chapter for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:43
msgid ""
"**component** --- Each release of Rust includes several \"components\", some "
"of which are required (like `rustc`) and some that are optional (like "
"[`clippy`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy)). See the [Components]"
"(components.md) chapter for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:47
msgid ""
"**profile** --- In order to make it easier to work with components, a "
"\"profile\" defines a grouping of components. See the [Profiles](profiles."
"md) chapter for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/index.md:51
msgid ""
"**proxy** ---  A wrapper for a common Rust component (like `rustc`), built "
"to forward CLI invocations to the active Rust toolchain. See the [Proxies]"
"(proxies.md) chapter for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:1
msgid "Channels"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust is released to three different \"channels\": stable, beta, and nightly. "
"The stable releases are made every 6 weeks (with occasional point releases). "
"Beta releases are the version that will appear in the next stable release. "
"Nightly releases are made every night. See [The Rust Book](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/book/appendix-07-nightly-rust.html) for more details on Rust's "
"train release model. The release schedule is posted to the [Rust Forge]"
"(https://forge.rust-lang.org/). `rustup` assists with installing different "
"channels, keeping them up-to-date, and easily switching between them."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:11
msgid ""
"After a release channel has been installed, `rustup` can be used to update "
"the installed version to the latest release on that channel. See the "
"[Keeping rust up to date](../basics.md#keeping-rust-up-to-date) section for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:15
msgid ""
"`rustup` can also install specific versions of Rust, such as `1.45.2` or "
"`nightly-2020-07-27`. See the [Toolchains](toolchains.md) chapter for more "
"information on installing different channels and releases. See the "
"[Overrides](../overrides.md) chapter for details on switching between "
"toolchains and pinning your project to a specific toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:26
msgid "Working with nightly Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:28
msgid ""
"`rustup` gives you easy access to the nightly compiler and its [experimental "
"features](https://doc.rust-lang.org/unstable-book/). To add it just run "
"`rustup toolchain install nightly`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:50
msgid ""
"Now Rust nightly is installed, but not activated. To test it out you can run "
"a command from the nightly toolchain like"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:58
msgid ""
"But more likely you want to use it for a while. To switch to nightly "
"globally, change [the default](../overrides.md#default-toolchain) with "
"`rustup default nightly`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:70
msgid ""
"Now any time you run `cargo` or `rustc` you will be running the nightly "
"compiler."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:73
msgid ""
"With nightly installed any time you run `rustup update`, the nightly channel "
"will be updated in addition to stable:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:90
msgid "Nightly availability"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:92
msgid ""
"Nightly toolchains may fail to build, so for any given date and target "
"platform there may not be a toolchain available. Furthermore, nightly builds "
"may be published with missing non-default [components](components.md) (such "
"as [`clippy`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy)). As such, it can be "
"difficult to find fully-working nightlies. Use the [rustup-components-"
"history](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup-components-history/) project to "
"find the build status of recent nightly toolchains and components."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:99
msgid ""
"When you attempt to install or update the `nightly` channel, `rustup` will "
"check if a required or previously installed component is missing. If it is "
"missing, `rustup` will automatically search for an older release that "
"contains the required components. There are several ways to change this "
"behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:104
msgid ""
"Use the `--force` flag to `rustup toolchain install` to force it to install "
"the most recent version even if there is a missing component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:106
msgid ""
"Use the `--profile` flag to `rustup toolchain install` to use a different "
"profile that does not contain the missing component. For example, `--"
"profile=minimal` should always work, as the minimal set is required to "
"exist. See the [Profiles](profiles.md) chapter for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:110
msgid ""
"Install a specific date that contains the components you need. For example, "
"`rustup toolchain install nightly-2020-07-27`. You can then use [overrides]"
"(../overrides.md) to pin to that specific release."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:1
msgid "Components"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:3
msgid ""
"Each [toolchain](toolchains.md) has several \"components\", some of which "
"are required (like `rustc`) and some that are optional (like [`clippy`]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy)). The `rustup component` command "
"is used to manage the installed components. For example, run `rustup "
"component list` to see a list of available and installed components."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:9
msgid ""
"Components can be added when installing a toolchain with the `--component` "
"flag. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:16
msgid ""
"Components can be added to an already-installed toolchain with the `rustup "
"component` command:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:23
msgid ""
"To make it easier to choose which components are installed, `rustup` has the "
"concept of \"profiles\" which provide named groupings of different "
"components. See the [Profiles](profiles.md) chapter for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:27
msgid ""
"Most components have a target-triple suffix, such as `rustc-x86_64-apple-"
"darwin`, to signify the platform the component is for."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:30
msgid ""
"The set of available components may vary with different releases and "
"toolchains. The following is an overview of the different components:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:33
msgid ""
"`rustc` --- The Rust compiler and [Rustdoc](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"rustdoc/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:34
msgid ""
"`cargo` --- [Cargo](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/) is a package manager "
"and build tool."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:35
msgid ""
"`rustfmt` --- [Rustfmt](https://github.com/rust-lang/rustfmt) is a tool for "
"automatically formatting code."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:36
msgid ""
"`rust-std` --- This is the Rust [standard library](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"std/). There is a separate `rust-std` component for each target that `rustc` "
"supports, such as `rust-std-x86_64-pc-windows-msvc`. See the [Cross-"
"compilation](../cross-compilation.md) chapter for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:40
msgid ""
"`rust-docs` --- This is a local copy of the [Rust documentation](https://doc."
"rust-lang.org/). Use the `rustup doc` command to open the documentation in a "
"web browser. Run `rustup doc --help` for more options."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:43
msgid ""
"`rust-analyzer` --- [rust-analyzer](https://rust-analyzer.github.io/) is a "
"language server that provides support for editors and IDEs."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:45
msgid ""
"`clippy` --- [Clippy](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy) is a lint "
"tool that provides extra checks for common mistakes and stylistic choices."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:47
msgid ""
"`miri` --- [Miri](https://github.com/rust-lang/miri/) is an experimental "
"Rust interpreter, which can be used for checking for undefined-behavior."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:49
msgid ""
"`rust-src` --- This is a local copy of the source code of the Rust standard "
"library. This can be used by some tools, such as [rust-analyzer](https://"
"rust-analyzer.github.io/), to provide auto-completion for functions within "
"the standard library; [Miri](https://github.com/rust-lang/miri/) which is a "
"Rust interpreter; and Cargo's experimental [build-std](https://doc.rust-lang."
"org/nightly/cargo/reference/unstable.html#build-std) feature, which allows "
"you to rebuild the standard library locally."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:54
msgid ""
"`rust-mingw` --- This contains a linker and platform libraries for building "
"on the `x86_64-pc-windows-gnu` platform."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:56
msgid ""
"`llvm-tools` --- This component contains a collection of [LLVM](https://llvm."
"org/) tools. **This component has not been stabilized and may change in the "
"future and is provided as-is.** Availability of individual LLVM tools may "
"change over LLVM versions (including removal of specific LLVM tools), and "
"**is not subject to compiler or toolchain stability guarantees**. See "
"[\\#85658](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/85658)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:62
msgid ""
"`rustc-dev` --- This component contains the compiler as a library. Most "
"users will not need this; it is only needed for development _of_ tools that "
"link to the compiler, such as making modifications to [Clippy](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:66
msgid "Previous components"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:68
msgid ""
"See [here](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup/devel/concepts/components."
"html#previous-components) for the latest version of this section."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:71
msgid ""
"These components have been deprecated and are not published in new Rust "
"releases."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:73
msgid ""
"`rls` --- [RLS](https://github.com/rust-lang/rls) is a language server that "
"is deprecated and has been replaced by rust-analyzer."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:75
msgid ""
"`rust-analysis` --- Metadata about the standard library, used by [RLS]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rls)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:76
msgid ""
"The `wasm32-wasi` target --- It has been [renamed](https://blog.rust-lang."
"org/2024/04/09/updates-to-rusts-wasi-targets.html) to `wasm32-wasip1`."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:80
msgid "Component availability"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/components.md:82
msgid ""
"Not all components are available for all toolchains. Especially on the "
"nightly channel, some components may not be included if they are in a broken "
"state. The current status of all the components may be found on the [rustup "
"components history](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup-components-history/) "
"page. See the [Nightly availability](channels.md#nightly-availability) "
"section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:1
msgid "Profiles"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:3
msgid ""
"`rustup` has the concept of \"profiles\". They are groups of [components]"
"(components.md) you can choose to download while installing a new Rust "
"toolchain. The profiles available at this time are `minimal`, `default`, and "
"`complete`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:7
msgid ""
"The **minimal** profile includes as few components as possible to get a "
"working compiler (`rustc`, `rust-std`, and `cargo`). It's recommended to use "
"this component on Windows systems if you don't use local documentation (the "
"large number of files can cause issues with some Antivirus systems), and in "
"CI."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:12
msgid ""
"The **default** profile includes all of components in the **minimal** "
"profile, and adds `rust-docs`, `rustfmt`, and `clippy`. This profile will be "
"used by `rustup` by default, and it's the one recommended for general use."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:15
msgid ""
"The **complete** profile includes all the components available through "
"`rustup`. This should never be used, as it includes _every_ component ever "
"included in the metadata and thus will almost always fail. If you are "
"looking for a way to install devtools such as `miri` or IDE integration "
"tools (`rust-analyzer`), you should use the `default` profile and install "
"the needed additional components manually, either by using `rustup component "
"add` or by using `-c` when installing the toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:23
msgid ""
"To change the profile `rustup install` uses by default, you can use the "
"`rustup set profile` command. For example, to select the minimal profile you "
"can use:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:31
msgid ""
"You can also directly select the profile used when installing a toolchain "
"with:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/profiles.md:37
msgid ""
"It's also possible to choose the default profile when installing `rustup` "
"for the first time, either interactively by choosing the \"Customize "
"installation\" option or programmatically by passing the `--profile=<name>` "
"flag. Profiles will only affect newly installed toolchains: as usual it will "
"be possible to install individual components later with: `rustup component "
"add`."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:1
msgid "Proxies"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:3
msgid ""
"`rustup` provides a number of wrappers for common Rust tools. These are "
"called _proxies_ and represent commands which are provided by the various "
"[components](components.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:7
msgid "The list of proxies is currently static in `rustup` and is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:11
msgid ""
"`rustc` is the compiler for the Rust programming language, provided by the "
"project itself and comes from the `rustc` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:13
msgid ""
"`rustdoc` is a tool distributed in the `rustc` component which helps you to "
"generate documentation for Rust projects."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:15
msgid ""
"`cargo` is the Rust package manager which downloads your Rust package’s "
"dependencies, compiles your packages, makes distributable packages, and "
"uploads them to crates.io (the Rust community’s package registry). It comes "
"from the `cargo` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:17
msgid ""
"`rust-lldb`, `rust-gdb`, and `rust-gdbgui` are simple wrappers around the "
"`lldb`, `gdb`, and `gdbgui` debuggers respectively. The wrappers enable some "
"pretty-printing of Rust values and add some convenience features to the "
"debuggers by means of their scripting interfaces."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:19
msgid ""
"`rust-analyzer` is part of the Rust IDE integration tooling. It implements "
"the language-server protocol to permit IDEs and editors such as Visual "
"Studio Code, Vim, or Emacs, access to the semantics of the Rust code you are "
"editing. It comes from the `rust-analyzer` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:21
msgid ""
"`cargo-clippy` and `clippy-driver` are related to the `clippy` linting tool "
"which provides extra checks for common mistakes and stylistic choices and it "
"comes from the `clippy` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:23
msgid ""
"`cargo-miri` is an experimental interpreter for Rust's mid-level "
"intermediate representation (MIR) and it comes from the `miri` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/proxies.md:25
msgid ""
"`rls` is a deprecated IDE tool that has been replaced by `rust-analyzer`. It "
"comes from the `rls` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:1
msgid "Toolchains"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:3
msgid ""
"Many `rustup` commands deal with _toolchains_, a single installation of the "
"Rust compiler. `rustup` supports multiple types of toolchains. The most "
"basic track the official release [channels](channels.md): _stable_, _beta_ "
"and _nightly_; but `rustup` can also install toolchains from the official "
"archives, for alternate host platforms, and from local builds."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:11
msgid "Toolchain specification"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:13
msgid "Standard release channel toolchain names have the following form:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:25
msgid ""
"'channel' is a named release channel, a major and minor version number such "
"as `1.42`, or a fully specified version number, such as `1.42.0`. Channel "
"names can be optionally appended with an archive date, as in "
"`nightly-2014-12-18`, in which case the toolchain is downloaded from the "
"archive for that date."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:30
msgid ""
"Finally, the host may be specified as a target tuple. This is most useful "
"for installing a 32-bit compiler on a 64-bit platform, or for installing the "
"[MSVC-based toolchain](https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install?"
"platform_override=win) on Windows. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:38
msgid ""
"For convenience, elements of the target tuple that are omitted will be "
"inferred, so the above could be written:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:45
msgid ""
"Toolchain names that don't name a channel instead can be used to name "
"[custom toolchains](#custom-toolchains)."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:51
msgid "Custom toolchains"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:53
msgid ""
"For convenience of developers working on Rust itself, `rustup` can manage "
"local builds of the Rust toolchain. To teach `rustup` about your build, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:60
msgid ""
"For example, on Ubuntu you might clone `rust-lang/rust` into `~/rust`, build "
"it, and then run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:68
msgid ""
"Now you can name `my-toolchain` as any other `rustup` toolchain. Create a "
"`rustup` toolchain for each of your `rust-lang/rust` workspaces and test "
"them easily with `rustup run my-toolchain rustc`."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/toolchains.md:72
msgid ""
"Because the `rust-lang/rust` tree does not include Cargo, _when `cargo` is "
"invoked for a custom toolchain and it is not available, `rustup` will "
"attempt to use `cargo` from one of the release channels_, preferring "
"'nightly', then 'beta' or 'stable'."
msgstr ""

#: src/configuration.md:1
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/configuration.md:3
msgid ""
"Rustup has a [TOML](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml) settings file at "
"`${RUSTUP_HOME}/settings.toml` (which defaults to `~/.rustup` or "
"`%USERPROFILE%/.rustup`). The schema for this file is not part of the public "
"interface for rustup - the rustup CLI should be used to query and set "
"settings."
msgstr ""

#: src/configuration.md:8
msgid ""
"On Unix operating systems a fallback settings file is consulted for some "
"settings. This fallback file is located at `/etc/rustup/settings.toml` and "
"currently can define only `default_toolchain`."
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:1
msgid "Cross-compilation"
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust [supports a great number of platforms](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"nightly/rustc/platform-support.html). For many of these platforms The Rust "
"Project publishes binary releases of the standard library, and for some the "
"full compiler. `rustup` gives easy access to all of them."
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:9
msgid ""
"When you first install a toolchain, `rustup` installs only the standard "
"library for your _host_ platform - that is, the architecture and operating "
"system you are presently running. To compile to other platforms you must "
"install other _target_ platforms. This is done with the `rustup target add` "
"command. For example, to add the Android target:"
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:21
msgid ""
"With the `arm-linux-androideabi` target installed you can then build for "
"Android with Cargo by passing the `--target` flag, as in `cargo build --"
"target=arm-linux-androideabi`."
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:25
msgid ""
"Note that `rustup target add` only installs the Rust standard library for a "
"given target. There are typically other tools necessary to cross-compile, "
"particularly a linker. For example, to cross compile to Android the [Android "
"NDK](https://developer.android.com/tools/sdk/ndk/index.html) must be "
"installed. In the future, `rustup` will provide assistance installing the "
"NDK components as well. See the [target section](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"cargo/reference/config.html#target) of the `cargo` configuration for how to "
"setup a linker to use for a certain target."
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:35
msgid ""
"To install a target for a toolchain that isn't the default toolchain use the "
"`--toolchain` argument of `rustup target add`, like so:"
msgstr ""

#: src/cross-compilation.md:42
msgid ""
"To see a list of available targets, `rustup target list`. To remove a "
"previously-added target, `rustup target remove`."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:1
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:3
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_LOG` (default: none). Enables Rustup's \"custom logging mode\". In "
"this mode, the verbosity of Rustup's log lines can be specified with "
"`tracing_subscriber`'s [directive syntax](https://docs.rs/tracing-subscriber/"
"latest/tracing_subscriber/filter/struct.EnvFilter.html#directives). For "
"example, set `RUSTUP_LOG=rustup=DEBUG` to receive log lines from `rustup` "
"itself with a maximal verbosity of `DEBUG`."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:8
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_HOME` (default: `~/.rustup` or `%USERPROFILE%/.rustup`). Sets the "
"root `rustup` folder, used for storing installed toolchains and "
"configuration options."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:12
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TOOLCHAIN` (default: none). If set, will [override](overrides.md) "
"the toolchain used for all rust tool invocations. A toolchain with this name "
"should be installed, or invocations will fail. This can specify custom "
"toolchains, installable toolchains, or the absolute path to a toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:17
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_DIST_SERVER` (default: `https://static.rust-lang.org`). Sets the "
"root URL for downloading static resources related to Rust. You can change "
"this to instead use a local mirror, or to test the binaries from the staging "
"directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:22
msgid ""
"~~`RUSTUP_DIST_ROOT`~~ _deprecated_ (default: `https://static.rust-lang.org/"
"dist`). Use `RUSTUP_DIST_SERVER` instead."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:25
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_UPDATE_ROOT` (default `https://static.rust-lang.org/rustup`). Sets "
"the root URL for downloading self-update."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:28
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_VERSION` (default: none). Overrides the rustup version (e.g. "
"`1.27.1`) to be downloaded when executing `rustup-init.sh` or `rustup self "
"update`."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:31
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_IO_THREADS` _unstable_ (default: reported cpu count, max 8). Sets "
"the number of threads to perform close IO in. Set to `1` to force single-"
"threaded IO for troubleshooting, or an arbitrary number to override "
"automatic detection."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:36
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TRACE_DIR` _unstable_ (default: no tracing). Enables tracing and "
"determines the directory that traces will be written too. Traces are of the "
"form PID.trace. Traces can be read by the Catapult project [tracing viewer]"
"(https://github.com/catapult-project/catapult/blob/master/tracing/README.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:40
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TERM_COLOR` (default: `auto`). Controls whether colored output is "
"used in the terminal. Set to `auto` to use colors only in tty streams, to "
"`always` to always enable colors, or to `never` to disable colors."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:44
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_UNPACK_RAM` _unstable_ (default: free memory or 500MiB if unable to "
"tell, min 210MiB). Caps the amount of RAM (in bytes) `rustup` will use for "
"IO tasks while unpacking."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:47
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_NO_BACKTRACE`. Disables backtraces on non-panic errors even when "
"`RUST_BACKTRACE` is set."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:50
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_PERMIT_COPY_RENAME` _unstable_. When set, allows rustup to fall-back "
"to copying files if attempts to `rename` result in cross-device link errors. "
"These errors occur on OverlayFS, which is used by [Docker](https://docs."
"docker.com/storage/storagedriver/overlayfs-driver/#modifying-files-or-"
"directories). This feature sacrifices some transactions protections and may "
"be removed at any point. Linux only."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:56
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_AUTO_INSTALL` (default: 1) When set to `1`, installs the active "
"toolchain when it is absent. Set this value to `0` to disable automatic "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:60
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_HARDLINK_PROXIES` _unstable_. When set, rustup will not attempt to "
"symlink proxies and instead always use hardlinks. If you find this fixes a "
"problem, then please report the issue on the [rustup issue tracker](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rustup/issues)."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:64
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TERM_PROGRESS_WHEN` (default: `auto`). Controls whether progress "
"bars are shown or not. Set to `always` to always enable progress bars, and "
"to `never` to disable them."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:67
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TERM_WIDTH` (default: none). Allows to override the terminal width "
"for progress bars."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:69
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_DOWNLOAD_TIMEOUT` _unstable_ (default: 180). Allows to override the "
"default timeout (in seconds) for downloading components."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:72
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_CONCURRENT_DOWNLOADS` _unstable_ (default: 2). Controls the number "
"of downloads made concurrently."
msgstr ""

#: src/environment-variables.md:75
msgid ""
"`RUSTUP_TOOLCHAIN_SOURCE` _unstable_. Set by rustup to tell proxied tools "
"how `RUSTUP_TOOLCHAIN` was determined. Non-rustup tools should not set this "
"environment variable, except insofar as to mirror an earlier invocation from "
"rustup."
msgstr ""

