#: src/faq.md:1
msgid "FAQ"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:3
msgid "Is this an official Rust project?"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:5
msgid ""
"Yes. rustup is an official Rust project. It is the recommended way to "
"install Rust at https://www.rust-lang.org."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:8
msgid "How is this related to multirust?"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:10
msgid ""
"rustup is the successor to [multirust](https://github.com/brson/multirust). "
"rustup began as multirust-rs, a rewrite of multirust from shell script to "
"Rust, by [Diggory Blake](https://github.com/Diggsey), and is now maintained "
"by The Rust Project."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:17
msgid "Can rustup download the Rust source code?"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:19
msgid ""
"The source for Rust's standard library can be obtained by running `rustup "
"component add rust-src`. It will be downloaded to the `<toolchain root>/lib/"
"rustlib/src/rust` directory of the current toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:23
msgid ""
"The source for the compiler and tools must be obtained from the [Rust "
"repository](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/) or the standalone [source "
"tarballs](https://forge.rust-lang.org/infra/other-installation-methods."
"html#source-code)."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:29
msgid "rustup fails with Windows error 32"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:31
msgid ""
"If `rustup` fails with Windows error 32, it may be due to antivirus scanning "
"in the background. Disable antivirus scanner and try again."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:34
msgid ""
"I get \"error: could not remove 'rustup-bin' file: 'C:\\Users\\USER\\\\."
"cargo\\bin\\rustup.exe'\""
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:36
msgid ""
"If `rustup` fails to self-update in this way it's usually because RLS is "
"running (your editor is open and running RLS). The solution is to stop RLS "
"(by closing your editor) and try again."
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:40
msgid "rustup exited successfully but I can't run `rustc --version`"
msgstr ""

#: src/faq.md:42
msgid ""
"Restart your shell. This will reload your `PATH` environment variable to "
"include Cargo's bin directory (`$CARGO_HOME/bin`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:1
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:3
msgid ""
"Follow the instructions at <https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install>. If "
"that doesn't work for you there are [other installation methods](other.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:6
msgid ""
"`rustup` installs `rustc`, `cargo`, `rustup` and other standard tools to "
"Cargo's `bin` directory. On Unix it is located at `$HOME/.cargo/bin` and on "
"Windows at `%USERPROFILE%\\.cargo\\bin`. This is the same directory that "
"`cargo install` will install Rust programs and Cargo plugins."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:11
msgid ""
"This directory will be in your `$PATH` environment variable, which means you "
"can run them from the shell without further configuration. Open a _new_ "
"shell and type the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:19
msgid ""
"If you see something like `rustc 1.19.0 (0ade33941 2017-07-17)` then you are "
"ready to Rust. If you decide Rust isn't your thing, you can completely "
"remove it from your system by running `rustup self uninstall`."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:25
msgid "Choosing where to install"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:27
msgid ""
"`rustup` allows you to customise your installation by setting the "
"environment variables `CARGO_HOME` and `RUSTUP_HOME` before running the "
"`rustup-init` executable. As mentioned in the [Environment Variables](../"
"environment-variables.md) section, `RUSTUP_HOME` sets the root `rustup` "
"folder, which is used for storing installed toolchains and configuration "
"options. `CARGO_HOME` contains cache files used by [cargo](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/cargo/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:33
msgid ""
"Note that you will need to ensure these environment variables are always set "
"and that `CARGO_HOME/bin` is in the `$PATH` environment variable when using "
"the toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:40
msgid "Installing nightly"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:42
msgid ""
"If you specify the [nightly channel](../concepts/channels.md) when "
"installing `rustup`, the `rustup-init` script will do a \"forced\" "
"installation by default. A \"forced\" installation means it will install the "
"nightly channel regardless of whether it might be missing [components](../"
"concepts/components.md) that you want. If you want to install rustup with "
"the nightly channel, and ensure it has the components that you want, you "
"will need to do this in two phases. For example, if you want to make a fresh "
"installation of `rustup` and then install `nightly` along with `clippy` or "
"`miri`, first install `rustup` without a toolchain:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:51
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --"
"default-toolchain none -y\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:55
msgid ""
"Next you can install `nightly` allowing `rustup` to downgrade until it finds "
"the components you need:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:62
msgid ""
"This can be used to great effect in CI, to get you a toolchain rapidly which "
"meets your criteria."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:68
msgid "Enable tab completion for Bash, Fish, Zsh, or PowerShell"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:70
msgid ""
"`rustup` now supports generating completion scripts for Bash, Fish, Zsh, and "
"PowerShell. See `rustup help completions` for full details, but the gist is "
"as simple as using one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:94
msgid ""
"**Note**: you may need to restart your shell in order for the changes to "
"take effect."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:97
msgid ""
"For `zsh`, you must then add the following line in your `~/.zshrc` before "
"`compinit`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:101
msgid "~/.zfunc"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/index.md:104
msgid ""
"In Xonsh you can reuse Fish completion by installing [xontrib-fish-completer]"
"(https://github.com/xonsh/xontrib-fish-completer)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:1
msgid "Already installed Rust?"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:3
msgid ""
"Other package managers also ship Rust, and you may wish to use the packaged "
"toolchain, such as for distribution package development. You may also wish "
"to use a `rustup`\\-managed toolchain such as nightly or beta. Normally, "
"`rustup` will complain that you already have Rust installed in `/usr` and "
"refuse to install. However, you can install Rust via `rustup` and have it "
"coexist with your packaged Rust toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:10
msgid "Set up rustup with an existing Rust toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:12
msgid ""
"When you initially install Rust with `rustup`, pass the `-y` option to make "
"it ignore the packaged Rust toolchain and install a `rustup`\\-managed "
"toolchain into `~/.cargo/bin`. Add that directory to your `$PATH` (or let "
"`rustup` do it for you by not passing `--no-modify-path`). Then, to tell "
"`rustup` about your system toolchain, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:22
msgid ""
"You can then use \"system\" as a `rustup` toolchain, just like \"nightly\". "
"For example, using the [toolchain override shorthand](../overrides."
"md#toolchain-override-shorthand), you can run `cargo +system build` to build "
"with the system toolchain, or `cargo +nightly build` to build with nightly."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:26
msgid ""
"If you wish to develop with the system toolchain (e.g. for distribution "
"packages), you may want to make it your [default toolchain](../overrides."
"md#default-toolchain):"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:33
msgid "Ensure the correct `$PATH` configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:35
msgid ""
"There are times when the above steps don't work, and you may see strange "
"error messages when running commands that should have been proxied by "
"rustup. For example, when running `cargo +stable --version`, you may "
"encounter the following error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:47
msgid ""
"This means `cargo` is currently not a `rustup` proxy, and your `$PATH` needs "
"to be fixed."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:50
msgid ""
"In fact, on any machine with rustup installed, you would like to have "
"**rustup proxies showing up first in `$PATH`**, shadowing any other Rust "
"installations. Don't worry: these shadowed installations can then be adopted "
"by rustup with the `rustup toolchain link` command as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:55
msgid ""
"The exact steps to be taken to make rustup proxies come first may vary "
"according to your system environment, but usually it is about changing the "
"evaluation order of certain lines in your shell configuration file(s)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:59
msgid ""
"To make it clearer, let's look at the example of a Mac with both regular "
"rustup fetched from [rustup.rs](https://rustup.rs) and homebrew-installed "
"`rust`. The **right way** to configure `.profile` in this environment would "
"be:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:68
msgid ""
"In this example, both of these lines _prepend_ to `$PATH`, so the last one "
"takes over, letting the rustup proxies shadow the homebrew-installed `rust`. "
"On the other hand, putting these lines the other way around will cause the "
"aforementioned error."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:73
msgid ""
"When in doubt, you can always debug your shell configuration by printing the "
"status of your current `$PATH` with `echo $PATH | xargs -n1` and paying "
"attention to the order of `$CARGO_HOME/bin` (which defaults to `$HOME/.cargo/"
"bin`) compared to your package manager's `bin` directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:78
msgid ""
"After the fix, the output of `cargo +stable --version` should be similar to "
"one of the following, depending on whether you have had the `stable` "
"toolchain installed:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:1
msgid "Other installation methods"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:3
msgid ""
"The primary installation method, as described at <https://rustup.rs>, "
"differs by platform:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:6
msgid ""
"On Windows, download and run the `rustup-init.exe` built for the [`x86_64-pc-"
"windows-msvc`](https://static.rust-lang.org/rustup/dist/x86_64-pc-windows-"
"msvc/rustup-init.exe) or [`aarch64-pc-windows-msvc`](https://static.rust-"
"lang.org/rustup/dist/aarch64-pc-windows-msvc/rustup-init.exe) target, "
"depending on your OS architecture. In general, this is the build of `rustup` "
"one should install on Windows. This will require [MSVC prerequisites]"
"(windows-msvc.html). If you would prefer to install GNU toolchains or the "
"i686 toolchains by default this can be modified at install time, either "
"interactively, with the `--default-host` flag, or after installation via "
"`rustup set default-host`."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:14
msgid ""
"On Unix, run `curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | "
"sh` in your shell. This downloads and runs [`rustup-init.sh`](https://static."
"rust-lang.org/rustup/rustup-init.sh), which in turn downloads and runs the "
"correct version of the `rustup-init` executable for your platform."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:23
msgid ""
"`rustup-init` accepts arguments, which can be passed through the shell "
"script. Some examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:26
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"$ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --"
"help\n"
"$ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --no-"
"modify-path\n"
"$ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --"
"default-toolchain nightly\n"
"$ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --"
"default-toolchain none\n"
"$ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh -s -- --"
"profile minimal --default-toolchain nightly\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

