#: src/installation/other.md:194
msgid ""
"Windows GNU builds require no additional software for basic use. However, "
"many library crates will not be able to compile until the full [MSYS2]"
"(https://www.msys2.org/) with MinGW has been installed."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:200
msgid ""
"MSVC builds of `rustup` additionally require an [installation of Visual "
"Studio 2019 or the Visual C++ Build Tools 2019](https://visualstudio."
"microsoft.com/downloads/). For Visual Studio, make sure to check the \"C++ "
"tools\" and \"Windows 10 SDK\" option."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:206
msgid "Self-compiled installation"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/other.md:208
msgid ""
"To install `rustup` from source, check out the git repository from <https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rustup> and run `cargo run --release`. Note that after "
"installation the `rustup` toolchains will supersede any pre-existing "
"toolchains by prepending `~/.cargo/bin` to the `PATH` environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:1
msgid "Windows"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:3
msgid ""
"`rustup` works the same on Windows as it does on Unix, but there are some "
"special considerations for Rust developers on Windows. As [mentioned on the "
"Rust download page](https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install?"
"platform_override=win), there are two [ABIs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Application_binary_interface) in use on Windows: the native (MSVC) ABI used "
"by [Visual Studio](https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/), and the GNU ABI "
"used by the [GCC toolchain](https://gcc.gnu.org/). Which version of Rust you "
"need depends largely on what C/C++ libraries you want to interoperate with: "
"for interop with software produced by Visual Studio use the MSVC build of "
"Rust; for interop with GNU software built using the [MinGW/MSYS2 toolchain]"
"(https://www.msys2.org/) use the GNU build."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:12
msgid ""
"When targeting the MSVC ABI, Rust additionally requires an [installation of "
"Visual Studio](windows-msvc.html) so `rustc` can use its linker and "
"libraries."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:15
msgid ""
"When targeting the GNU ABI, no additional software is strictly required for "
"basic use. However, many library crates will not be able to compile until "
"the full [MSYS2](https://www.msys2.org/) with MinGW has been installed."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:18
msgid ""
"By default `rustup` on Windows configures Rust to target the MSVC ABI, that "
"is a target tuple of either `i686-pc-windows-msvc`, `x86_64-pc-windows-"
"msvc`, or `aarch64-pc-windows-msvc` depending on the CPU architecture of the "
"host Windows OS. The toolchains that `rustup` chooses to install, unless "
"told otherwise through the [toolchain specification](../concepts/toolchains."
"md#toolchain-specification), will be compiled to run on that target tuple "
"host and will target that triple by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:25
msgid ""
"You can change this behavior with `rustup set default-host` or during "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:28
msgid "For example, to explicitly select the 32-bit MSVC host:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:34
msgid "Or to choose the 64 bit GNU toolchain:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:40
msgid ""
"Since the MSVC ABI provides the best interoperation with other Windows "
"software it is recommended for most purposes. The GNU toolchain is always "
"available, even if you don't use it by default. Just install it with `rustup "
"toolchain install`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:49
msgid ""
"You don't need to switch toolchains to support all windows targets though; a "
"single toolchain supports all four x86 windows targets:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows.md:59
msgid ""
"See the [Cross-compilation](../cross-compilation.md) chapter for more "
"details on specifying different targets with the same compiler."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:1
msgid "MSVC prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:3
msgid ""
"To compile programs into an exe file, Rust requires a linker, libraries and "
"Windows API import libraries. For `msvc` targets these can be acquired "
"through Visual Studio."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:6
msgid "Automatic install"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:8
msgid ""
"If you don't have Visual Studio already installed then [rustup-init](https://"
"rustup.rs) will offer to automatically install the prerequisites. Doing so "
"means you can skip the rest of this page. However, it installs Visual Studio "
"Community edition which may not be appropriate for all users. It is free for "
"individuals, academic and open source use, but not for other uses, such as "
"in proprietary enterprise software. Users should ask their organisation "
"which edition is right for them. See [licensing terms](https://visualstudio."
"microsoft.com/license-terms/) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:15
msgid "WinGet"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:17
msgid ""
"Alternatively Visual Studio can be installed via the [WinGet](https://learn."
"microsoft.com/en-us/windows/package-manager/winget/) package manager, which "
"should be available by default on recent versions of Windows. Run the "
"following command in powershell or the command prompt:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:20
msgid ""
"```\n"
"winget install --id Microsoft.VisualStudio.2022.Community --source winget --"
"force --override \"--add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.Tools.x86.x64 --"
"add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.Tools.ARM64 --add Microsoft."
"VisualStudio.Component.Windows11SDK.22621 --addProductLang En-us\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:24
msgid ""
"You can replace \"Community\" with \"BuildTools\" in the above command if "
"you already have a Visual Studio license."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:26
msgid "Missing Windows SDK"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:28
msgid ""
"If after running the above command the Windows 11 SDK is missing then you "
"may need to manually install it, which can also be done via WinGet. First "
"search for the available versions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:35
msgid "This should display a table of results. that will look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:45
msgid ""
"Pick the Id with the latest version and install that via `winget install`. "
"For example, to install `Microsoft.WindowsSDK.10.0.26100` run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:54
msgid "Manual install"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:56
msgid ""
"[Download Visual Studio](https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/). "
"Rust supports Visual Studio 2017 and later but it is recommended that you "
"use the latest version (currently 2022) for new projects. You can opt to "
"download only the Build Tools for Visual Studio, which does not include the "
"IDE. However this requires you already have a license to the Community, "
"Professional or Enterprise edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:61
msgid ""
"Once you've downloaded and started the installer, the easiest way to get "
"everything installed is to select \"Desktop Development with C++\". This "
"will include the necessary components. On the \"Language Packs\" tab, make "
"sure the English language pack is installed in addition to your preferred "
"language."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:65
msgid ""
"If you want more details on the installation process or want to further "
"customize the install then follow the walkthrough below. Otherwise complete "
"the Visual Studio install and continue with installing Rust."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:68
msgid "Walkthrough: Installing Visual Studio 2022"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:70
msgid ""
"This walkthrough uses the Community edition of Visual Studio but the "
"Professional, Enterprise and the Build Tools all work the same way."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:72
msgid ""
"The installer will start by linking to the [license](https://visualstudio."
"microsoft.com/license-terms/) and for your edition of Visual Studio and then "
"preparing the installer."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:74
msgid ""
"![Accept the license](images/step1.png) ![Installing the installer](images/"
"step2.png)"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/windows-msvc.md:77
msgid ""
"Once this finishes, you can then select the components to be installed. Here "
